# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] The ***Alma*-class ironclads** were a group of seven wooden-hulled, armored corvettes built for the French Navy in the mid to late 1860s.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] Three of the ships attempted to blockade Prussian ports in the Baltic Sea in 1870 during the Franco-Prussian War.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] Three others patrolled the North Sea and the Atlantic, while the last ship was en route to Japan when the war began and blockaded two small Prussian ships in a Japanese harbor.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] Afterwards they alternated periods of reserve and active commissions, many of them abroad.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] Three of the ships participated in the French occupation of Tunisia in 1881 while another helped to intimidate the Vietnamese Government into accepting status as a French protectorate and played a small role in the Sino-French War of 1884–85.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] The *Alma*-class ironclads were designed by Henri Dupuy de Lôme as improved versions of the armored corvette *Belliqueuse* suitable for foreign deployments.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] Unlike their predecessor the ships were true central battery ironclads as they were fitted with armored transverse bulkheads.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] The original plan for these ships was to have a two-deck battery with four 194-millimeter (7.6 in) guns on the battery deck and four 164-millimeter (6.5 in) guns mounted above them on the upper deck, one gun at each corner of the battery.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] This design was changed to substitute four barbettes for the upper battery, but the addition of armored bulkheads proved to be very heavy and the rear pair of barbettes had to be deleted to save weight.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] In partial compensation the 164-millimeter guns in the remaining forward barbettes were replaced by an additional pair of 194-millimeter guns.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] Like most ironclads of their era they were equipped with a metal-reinforced ram.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] The ships were built from the same general plan, but differed amongst themselves.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] Their crew numbered 316 officers and men.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] The *Alma*-class ships had a single horizontal return connecting-rod steam engine driving a single propeller.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] Their engine was powered by four oval boilers.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] Unlike the single funnels of the others, *Jeanne d'Arc* and *Thétis* had two funnels, mounted side by side.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] They were barque-rigged with three masts and had a sail area between 1,338–1,454 square meters (14,400–15,650 sq ft).
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] The ships mounted four of their 194-millimeter Modèle 1864 breech-loading guns in the central battery on the battery deck.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] The other two 194-millimeter guns were mounted in barbettes on the upper deck, sponsoned out over the sides of the ship.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] The four 120-millimeter (4.7 in) guns were also mounted on the upper deck.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] *Alma* is the only ship positively known to have exchanged her 194 mm guns for newer Modèle 1870 guns.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] The armor-piercing shell of the 20-caliber Mle 1870 gun weighed 165.3 pounds (75 kg) while the gun itself weighed 7.83 long tons (7.96 t).
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] The gun fired its shell at a muzzle velocity of 1,739 ft/s (530 m/s) and was credited with the ability to penetrate a nominal 12.5 inches (320 mm) of wrought iron armour at the muzzle.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] The guns could fire both solid shot and explosive shells.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] The *Alma*-class ships had a complete 150-millimeter (5.9 in) wrought iron waterline belt, approximately 2.4 meters (7.9 ft) high.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] The sides of the battery itself were armored with 120 millimeters (4.7 in) of wrought iron and the ends of the battery were closed by bulkheads of the same thickness.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] The barbette armor was 100 millimeters (3.9 in) thick, backed by 240 millimeters (9.4 in) of wood.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] The unarmored portions of their sides were protected by 15-millimeter (0.6 in) iron plates.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] During the Franco-Prussian War of 1870–71 *Thétis*, *Jeanne d'Arc* and *Armide* were assigned to the Northern Squadron that attempted to blockade Prussian ports on the Baltic until ordered to return to Cherbourg on 16 September 1870.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] *Montcalm*, *Atalante*, and *Reine Blanche* cruised the North Sea and *Montcalm* later captured the Prussian Barque *Union* and watched a Prussian corvette in Portuguese waters.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] *Alma* was en route to the Far East when the war began and she blockaded a pair of Prussian corvettes in Yokohama harbor once she arrived at Japan.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] After the end of the war many of the ships were placed in reserve or sent to foreign stations, often as the flagship.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] During the Third Carlist War of 1872–76 *Thétis*, *Reine Blanche* and *Jeanne d'Arc* spent time in Spanish waters where they could protect French citizens and interests.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] In 1875, the latter ship rammed and sank the dispatch vessel *Forfait*.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] On 3 July 1877 *Thétis* rammed *Reine Blanche* who had to be run ashore to prevent her from sinking.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] Further abroad *Reine Blanche* and *Alma* bombarded the Tunisian port of Sfax in July 1881 as part of the French occupation of Tunisia.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] *Atalante* participated in the Battle of Thuận An in August 1883.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] This was an attack by the French on the forts defending the mouth of the Perfume River, leading to the Vietnamese capital of Huế in an attempt to intimidate the Vietnamese government.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/alma-class-ironclad] During the Sino-French War of 1884–85 the ship was in Huế in early September 1884, but she carried Admiral Amédée Courbet to Keelung, Taiwan on 23 September.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The **Battle of Hampton Roads**, also referred to as the **Battle of the *Monitor* and *Merrimack*** or the **Battle of Ironclads**, was a naval battle during the American Civil War.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The battle was fought over two days, March 8 and 9, 1862, in Hampton Roads, a roadstead in Virginia where the Elizabeth and Nansemond rivers meet the James River just before it flows into Chesapeake Bay by the city of Norfolk.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The battle was a part of the effort of the Confederacy to break the Union blockade, which had cut off Virginia's largest cities and major industrial centers, Norfolk and Richmond, from international trade.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] This battle was significant in that it was the first combat between ironclad warships, the USS *Monitor* and CSS *Virginia*.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The Confederate fleet consisted of the ironclad ram *Virginia* (built from remnants of the burned steam frigate USS *Merrimack*) and several supporting vessels.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] On the first day of battle, they were opposed by several conventional, wooden-hulled ships of the Union Navy.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] On that day, the *Virginia* was able to destroy two ships of the Union flotilla, USS *Congress* and USS *Cumberland*, and was about to attack a third, USS *Minnesota*, which had run aground.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] However, the action was halted by darkness and falling tide, so *Virginia* retired to take care of her few wounded—which included her captain, Flag Officer Franklin Buchanan—and repair her minimal battle damage.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Determined to complete the destruction of *Minnesota*, Catesby ap Roger Jones, acting as captain in Buchanan's absence, returned the ship to the fray the next morning, March 9.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] During the night, however, the ironclad *Monitor* had arrived and had taken a position to defend *Minnesota*.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] When *Virginia* approached, *Monitor* intercepted her.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The two ironclads fought for about three hours, with neither able to inflict significant damage on the other.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The duel ended indecisively, *Virginia* returning to her home at the Gosport Navy Yard for repairs and strengthening, and *Monitor* to her station defending *Minnesota*.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The ships did not fight again, and the blockade remained in place.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The battle received worldwide attention, having immediate effects on navies around the world.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The preeminent naval powers, Great Britain and France, halted further construction of wooden-hulled ships, and others followed suit.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Although Britain and France had been engaged in an iron-clad arms race since the 1830s, the Battle of Hampton Roads signaled a new age of naval warfare had arrived for the whole world.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] A new type of warship, monitor, was produced on the principle of the original.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The use of a small number of very heavy guns, mounted so that they could fire in all directions, was first demonstrated by *Monitor* but soon became standard in warships of all types.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Shipbuilders also incorporated rams into the designs of warship hulls for the rest of the century.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] On April 19, 1861, shortly after the outbreak of hostilities at Charleston Harbor, US President Abraham Lincoln proclaimed a blockade of ports in the seceded states.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] On April 27, after Virginia and North Carolina had also passed ordinances of secession, the blockade was extended to include their ports also.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Even before the extension, local troops had seized the Norfolk area and threatened the Gosport Navy Yard in Portsmouth.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The commandant there, Captain Charles S.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] McCauley, though loyal to the Union, was immobilized by advice he received from his subordinate officers, most of whom were in favor of secession.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Although he had orders from (Union) Secretary of the Navy Gideon Welles to move his ships to Northern ports, he refused to act until April 20, when he gave orders to scuttle the ships in the yard and destroy its facilities.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] At least nine ships were burned, among them the screw frigate USS *Merrimack*.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Merrimack* burned only to the waterline, however, and her engines were more or less intact.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The destruction of the navy yard was mostly ineffective; in particular, the large drydock there was relatively undamaged and soon could be restored.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Without firing a shot, the advocates of secession had gained for the South its largest navy yard, as well as the hull and engines of what would be in time its most famous warship.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] They had also seized more than a thousand heavy guns, plus gun carriages and large quantities of gunpowder.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] With Norfolk and its navy yard in Portsmouth, the Confederacy controlled the southern side of Hampton Roads.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] To prevent Union warships from attacking the yard, the Confederates set up batteries at Sewell's Point and Craney Island, at the juncture of the Elizabeth River with the James.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] (See map.) The Union retained possession of Fort Monroe, at Old Point Comfort on the Virginia Peninsula.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] They also held a small man-made island known as the Rip Raps, on the far side of the channel opposite Fort Monroe, and on this island they completed another fort, named Fort Wool.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] With Fort Monroe went control of the lower Peninsula as far as Newport News.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Forts Monroe and Wool gave the Union forces control of the entrance to Hampton Roads.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The blockade, initiated on April 30, 1861, cut off Norfolk and Richmond from the sea almost completely.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] To further the blockade, the Union Navy stationed some of its most powerful warships in the roadstead.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] There, they were under the shelter of the shore-based guns of Fort Monroe and the batteries at Hampton and Newport News and out of the range of the guns at Sewell's Point and Craney Island.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] For most of the first year of the war, the Confederacy could do little to oppose or dislodge them.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] When steam propulsion began to be applied to warships, naval constructors renewed their interest in armor for their vessels.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Experiments had been tried with armor during the Crimean War (1853–1856), just prior to the American Civil War, and the British and French navies had each built armored ships and were planning to build others.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] In 1860 the French Navy commissioned *La Gloire*, the world's first ocean-going ironclad warship.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Great Britain followed a year later with HMS *Warrior*, the world's first armor-plated iron-hulled warship.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The use of armor remained controversial, however, and the United States Navy was generally reluctant to embrace the new technology.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] When the Civil War broke out in 1861, Confederate Secretary of the Navy Stephen R.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Mallory was an early enthusiast for the advantages of armor.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] As he looked upon it, the Confederacy could not match the industrial North in numbers of ships at sea, so they would have to compete by building vessels that individually outclassed those of the Union.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Mallory gathered about himself a group of men who could put his vision into practice, among them John M.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] When Mallory's men searched the South for factories that could build engines to drive the heavy ships that he wanted, they found no place to do it immediately.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] At the best facility, the Tredegar Iron Works in Richmond, building engines from scratch would take at least a year.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Upon learning this, Williamson suggested taking the engines from the hulk of *Merrimack*, recently raised from the bed of the Elizabeth River.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] His colleagues promptly accepted his suggestion and expanded it, proposing that the design of their projected ironclad be adapted to the hull.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Porter produced the revised plans, which were submitted to Mallory for approval.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] On July 11, 1861, the new design was accepted, and work began almost immediately.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The burned-out hull was towed into the graving dock that the Union Navy had failed to destroy.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] During the subsequent conversion process, the plans developed further, incorporating an iron ram fitted to the prow.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The re-modeled ship's offense, in addition to the ram, consisted of 10 guns: six 9 in (230 mm) smooth-bore Dahlgrens, two 6.4 in (160 mm) and two 7 in (180 mm) Brooke rifles.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Trials showed that these rifles firing solid shot would pierce up to eight inches of armor plating.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The Tredegar Iron works could produce both solid shot and shell, and since it was believed that *Virginia* would face only wooden ships, she was given only the explosive shell.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The armor plating, originally meant to be 1 in (25 mm) thick, was replaced by double plates, each 2 in (51 mm) thick, backed by 24 in (61 cm) of iron and pine.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The armor was pierced for 14 gunports: four on each broadside, three forward, and three aft.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The revisions, together with the usual problems associated with the transportation system of the South, resulted in delays that pushed out the launch date until February 3, 1862, and she was not commissioned until February 17, bearing the name CSS *Virginia*.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Intelligence that the Confederates were working to develop an ironclad caused consternation for the Union, but Secretary of the Navy Gideon Welles waited for Congress to meet to request permission to consider building armored vessels; Congress gave this permission on August 3, 1861.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Welles appointed a commission, which became known as the Ironclad Board, of three senior naval officers to choose among the designs that were submitted for consideration.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The three men were Captains Joseph Smith, Hiram Paulding, and Commander Charles Henry Davis.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The board considered seventeen designs, and chose to support three.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The first of the three to be completed, even though she was by far the most radical in design, was Swedish engineer and inventor John Ericsson's USS *Monitor*.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Ericsson's *Monitor*, which was built at Ericsson's yard on the East River in Greenpoint, Brooklyn, incorporated new and striking design features, the most significant of which were her armor and armament.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Instead of the large numbers of guns of rather small bore that had characterized warships in the past, Ericsson opted for only two guns of large caliber; he wanted to use 15 in (380 mm) guns, but had to settle for 11 in (280 mm) Dahlgren guns when the larger size were unavailable.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] These were mounted in a cylindrical turret, 20 ft (6.1 m) in diameter, 9 ft (2.7 m) high, covered with iron 8 in (200 mm) thick.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The whole rotated on a central spindle, and was moved by a steam engine that could be controlled by one man.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Ericsson was afraid that using the full 30 pounds of black powder to fire the huge cannon would raise the risk of an explosion in the turret.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] He demanded that a charge of 15 pounds be used to lessen this possibility.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] As with *Virginia*, trials found that a full charge would pierce armor plate, a finding that would have affected the outcome of the battle.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] A serious flaw in the design was the pilot house from which the ship would be conned, a small structure forward of the turret on the main deck.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Its presence meant that the guns could not fire directly forward, and it was isolated from other activities on the ship.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Despite the late start and the novelty of construction, *Monitor* was actually completed a few days before her counterpart *Virginia*, but the Confederates activated *Virginia* first.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The Confederate chain of command was anomalous.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Lieutenant Catesby ap Roger Jones had directed much of the conversion of *Merrimack* to *Virginia*, and he was disappointed when he was not named her captain.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Jones was retained aboard *Virginia*, but only as her executive officer.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Ordinarily, the ship would have been led by a captain of the Confederate States Navy, to be determined by the rigid seniority system that was in place.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Secretary Mallory wanted the aggressive Franklin Buchanan, but at least two other captains had greater seniority and had applied for the post.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Mallory evaded the issue by appointing Buchanan, head of the Office of Orders and Detail, flag officer in charge of the defenses of Norfolk and the James River.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] As such, he could control the movements of *Virginia*.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Technically, therefore, the ship went into the battle without a captain.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] On the Union side, command of the North Atlantic Blockading Squadron was held by Flag Officer Louis M.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] He had devised a plan for his frigates to engage *Virginia*, hoping to trap her in their crossfire.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] In the event, his plan broke down completely when four of the ships ran aground (one of them intentionally) in the confined waters of the roadstead.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] On the day of battle, Goldsborough was absent with the ships cooperating with the Burnside Expedition in North Carolina.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] In his absence, leadership fell to his second in command, Captain John Marston of USS *Roanoke*.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] As *Roanoke* was one of the ships that ran aground, Marston was unable to materially influence the battle, and his participation is often disregarded.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Most accounts emphasize the contribution of the captain of *Monitor*, John L.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Marston did, however, disregard orders from Secretary of War Gideon Welles to send the *Monitor* back to Washington, D.C., ahead of the battle, ensuring that it would be present to confront the *Merrimack*.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The battle began when the large and unwieldy CSS *Virginia* steamed into Hampton Roads on the morning of March 8, 1862.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Captain Buchanan intended to attack as soon as possible.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Virginia* was accompanied from her moorings on the Elizabeth River by *Raleigh* and *Beaufort*, and was joined at Hampton Roads by the James River Squadron, *Patrick Henry*, *Jamestown*, and *Teaser*.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] When they were passing the Union batteries at Newport News, *Patrick Henry* was temporarily disabled by a shot in her boiler that killed four of her crew.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] After repairs, she returned and rejoined the others.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] At this time, the Union Navy had five warships in the roadstead, in addition to several support vessels.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The sloop-of-war *Cumberland* and frigate *Congress* were anchored in the channel near Newport News.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Lawrence* and the steam frigates *Roanoke* and *Minnesota* were near Fort Monroe, along with the storeship *Brandywine*.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The latter three got under way as soon as they saw *Virginia* approaching, but all soon ran aground.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Lawrence* and *Roanoke* took no further important part in the battle.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Ramming *Cumberland* nearly resulted in the sinking of *Virginia* as well.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Virginia*'s bow ram got stuck in the enemy ship's hull, and as *Cumberland* listed and began to go down, she almost pulled *Virginia* under with her.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] At the time the vessels were locked, one of *Cumberland's* anchors was hanging directly above the foredeck of *Virginia*.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Had it come loose, the two ships might have gone down together.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Virginia* broke free, however, her ram breaking off as she backed away.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Buchanan next turned *Virginia* on *Congress*.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Seeing what had happened to *Cumberland*, Lieutenant Joseph B.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Smith, captain of *Congress*, ordered his ship grounded in shallow water.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] By this time, the James River Squadron, commanded by John Randolph Tucker, had arrived and joined *Virginia* in the attack on *Congress*.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] After an hour of unequal combat, the badly damaged *Congress* surrendered.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] While the surviving crewmen of *Congress* were being ferried off the ship, a Union battery on the north shore opened fire on *Virginia*.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] In retaliation, Buchanan ordered *Congress* fired upon with hot shot, cannonballs heated red-hot.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Congress* caught fire and burned throughout the rest of the day.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Near midnight, the flames reached her magazine and she exploded and sank, stern first.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Personnel losses included 110 killed or missing and presumed drowned.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Another 26 were wounded, of whom ten died within days.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Although she had not suffered anything like the damage she had inflicted, *Virginia* was not completely unscathed.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Shots from *Cumberland*, *Congress*, and Union troops ashore had riddled her smokestack, reducing her already low speed.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Two of her guns were disabled and several armor plates had been loosened.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Two of her crew were killed, and more were wounded.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] One of the wounded was Captain Buchanan, who stood out into the open top of the *Virginia*, thinking it was perfectly safe, which led to him having his left thigh pierced by a rifle shot.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Meanwhile, the James River Squadron had turned its attention to *Minnesota*, which had left Fort Monroe to join in the battle and had run aground.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] After *Virginia* had dealt with the surrender of *Congress*, she joined the James River Squadron despite her damage.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Because of her deep draft and the falling tide, however, *Virginia* was unable to get close enough to be effective, and darkness prevented the rest of the squadron from aiming their guns to any effect.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Virginia* left with the expectation of returning the next day and completing the task.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] She retreated into the safety of Confederate-controlled waters off Sewell's Point for the night, but had killed 250 enemy sailors and had lost two.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The Union had lost two ships and three were aground.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The United States Navy's greatest defeat (which would remain so until World War II) caused panic in Washington.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] As Lincoln's Cabinet met to discuss the disaster, the frightened Secretary of War Edwin Stanton told the others that *Virginia* might attack East coast cities, and even shell the White House before the meeting ended.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Welles assured his colleagues that they were safe as the ship could not traverse the Potomac River.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] He added that the Union also had an ironclad, and that it was heading to meet *Virginia*.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Both sides used the respite to prepare for the next day.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Virginia* put her wounded ashore and underwent temporary repairs.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Captain Buchanan was among the wounded, so command on the second day fell to his executive officer, Lieutenant Catesby ap Roger Jones.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Jones proved to be no less aggressive than the man he replaced.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] While *Virginia* was being prepared for renewal of the battle, and while *Congress* was still ablaze, *Monitor*, commanded by Lieutenant John L.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The Union ironclad had been rushed to Hampton Roads in hopes of protecting the Union fleet and preventing *Virginia* from threatening Union cities.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Captain Worden was informed that his primary task was to protect *Minnesota*, so *Monitor* took up a position near the grounded *Minnesota* and waited.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] "All on board felt we had a friend that would stand by us in our hour of trial," wrote Captain Gershom Jacques Van Brunt, *Minnesota*'s commander, in his official report the day after the engagement.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The next morning, at dawn on March 9, 1862, *Virginia* left her anchorage at Sewell's Point and moved to attack *Minnesota*, still aground.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] She was followed by the three ships of the James River Squadron.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] They found their course blocked, however, by the newly arrived *Monitor*.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] At first, Jones believed the strange craft—which one Confederate sailor mocked as "a cheese on a raft"—to be a boiler being towed from the *Minnesota*, not realizing the nature of his opponent.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Soon, however, it was apparent that he had no choice but to fight her.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The first shot of the engagement was fired at *Monitor* by *Virginia*.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The shot flew past *Monitor* and struck *Minnesota*, which answered with a broadside; this began what would be a lengthy engagement.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] "Again, all hands were called to quarters, and when she approached within a mile of us I opened upon her with my stern guns and made a signal to the *Monitor* to attack the enemy," Van Brunt added.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] After fighting for hours, mostly at close range, neither could overcome the other.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The armor of both ships proved adequate.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] In part, this was because each was handicapped in her offensive capabilities.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Buchanan, in *Virginia*, had not expected to fight another armored vessel, so his guns were supplied only with shell rather than armor-piercing shot.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Monitor*'s guns were used with the standard service charge of only 15 lb (6.8 kg) of powder, which did not give the projectile sufficient momentum to penetrate her opponent's armor.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Tests conducted after the battle showed that the Dahlgren guns could be operated safely and efficiently with charges of as much as 30 lb (14 kg).
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] However, despite this, as the two ironclads circled each other during the fight, *Monitor* was about to penetrate *Virginia'*s armor, but a misfiring of her weapons caused her to lose the advantage.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] At 10 AM that morning, *Virginia* grounded.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Monitor* opened fire on her vulnerable adversary, yet *Virginia* was able to scrape off the shore and rejoin the fight.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Later during the battle, Acting Master Louis N.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Stodder and officers Stimers and Truscott were inside the gun turret, discussing the course of action.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Stodder was leaning against the turret's inside wall when it took a direct hit.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Stodder was knocked unconscious and taken below, where it took him an hour to regain consciousness.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Stodder thus became the first man injured during the battle.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The battle finally ceased when a shell from *Virginia* struck the pilot house of *Monitor* and exploded, driving fragments of paint and iron through the viewing slits into Worden's eyes and temporarily blinding him.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] As no one else could see to command the ship, *Monitor* was forced to draw off.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The executive officer, Lieutenant Samuel Dana Greene, took over, and *Monitor* returned to the fight.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] In the period of command confusion, however, the crew of *Virginia* believed that their opponent had withdrawn.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Although *Minnesota* was still aground, the falling tide meant that she was out of reach.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Furthermore, *Virginia* had suffered enough damage to require extensive repair.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Convinced that his ship had won the day, Jones ordered her back to Norfolk.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] At about this time, *Monitor* returned, only to discover her opponent apparently giving up the fight.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Convinced that *Virginia* was quitting, with orders only to protect *Minnesota* and not to risk his ship unnecessarily, Greene did not pursue.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Thus, each side misinterpreted the moves of the other, and as a result each claimed victory.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] During the two-day engagement, USS *Minnesota* shot off 78 rounds of 10-inch solid shot; 67 rounds of 10-inch shells with 15-second fuse; 169 rounds of 9-inch solid shot; 180 9-inch shells with 15-second fuse; 35 8-inch shells with 15-second fuse and 5,567.5 pounds of service powder.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Three crew members, Alexander Winslow, Henry Smith and Dennis Harrington were killed during the battle and 16 were wounded.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] One of *Monitor*'s crew, Quartermaster Peter Williams, was awarded the Medal of Honor for his actions during the battle.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] By late March, the Union blockade fleet had been augmented by hastily refitted civilian ships, including the powerful SS *Vanderbilt*, SS *Arago*, SS *Illinois*, and SS *Ericsson*.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] These had been outfitted with rams and some iron plating.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] By late April, the new ironclads USRC *E.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Stevens* and USS *Galena* had also joined the blockade.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Each side considered how best to eliminate the threat posed by its opponent, and after *Virginia* returned each side tried to goad the other into attacking under unfavorable circumstances.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Both captains declined the opportunity to fight in waters not of their own choosing; Jeffers in particular was under positive orders not to risk his ship.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Consequently, each vessel spent the next month in what amounted to posturing.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Because the blockade was unbroken, Norfolk was of little strategic use to the Confederacy, and preliminary plans were laid to move the ship up the James River to the vicinity of Richmond.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Before adequate preparations could be made, the Confederate Army under Major General Benjamin Huger abandoned the city on May 9, without consulting anyone from the Navy.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Virginia*'s draft was too great to permit her to pass up the river, which had a depth of only 18 ft (5.5 m), and then only under favorable circumstances.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] She was trapped and could only be captured or sunk by the Union Navy.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Rather than allow either, Tattnall decided to destroy his own ship.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] He had her towed down to Craney Island in Portsmouth, where the gang were taken ashore, and then she was set afire.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] She burned through the rest of the day and most of the following night; shortly before dawn, the flames reached her magazine, and she blew up.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The victory claims that were made by both sides in the immediate aftermath of the Battle of Hampton Roads were based on misinterpretations of the opponent's behavior and have been dismissed by present-day historians.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] They agree that the result of the *Monitor*–*Virginia* encounter was not a victory for either side.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] As the combat between ironclads was the primary significance of the battle, the general verdict is that the overall result was a draw.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] All would acknowledge that the Southern fleet inflicted far more damage than it received, which would ordinarily imply that they had gained a tactical victory.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Compared to other Civil War battles, the loss of men and ships for the Union Navy would be considered a clear defeat.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] On the other hand, the blockade was not seriously threatened, so the entire battle can be regarded as an assault that ultimately failed.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] However, initially after the Battle of Hampton Roads, both the Confederate and Union media claimed victory for their own sides.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] A headline in a Boston newspaper the day after the battle read "The Merrimac Driven back by the Steamer!", implying a Union victory, while Confederate media focused on their original success against wooden Union ships.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Despite the battle ending in a stalemate, it was seen by both sides as an opportunity to raise war-time morale, especially since the ironclad ships were an exciting naval innovation that intrigued citizens.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Evaluation of the strategic results is likewise disputed.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The blockade was maintained, even strengthened, and *Virginia* was bottled up in Hampton Roads.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Because a decisive Confederate weapon was negated, some have concluded that the Union could claim a strategic victory.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Confederate advocates can counter, however, by arguing that *Virginia* had a military significance larger than the blockade, which was only a small part of the war in Tidewater Virginia.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Her mere presence was sufficient to close the James River to Federal incursions.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] She also imposed other constraints on the Peninsula Campaign then being mounted by the Union Army under General George B.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] McClellan, who worried that she could interfere with his positions on the York River.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Although his fears were baseless, they continued to affect the movements of his army until *Virginia* was destroyed.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Both days of the battle attracted attention from almost all the world's navies.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] USS *Monitor* became the prototype for the monitor warship type.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] She thus became the first of two ships whose names were applied to entire classes of their successors, the other being HMS *Dreadnought*.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Many more were built, including river monitors, and they played key roles in Civil War battles on the Mississippi and James rivers.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The US immediately started the construction of ten more monitors based on Ericsson's original larger plan, known as the *Passaic*-class monitors.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] More than 20 additional monitors were built by the Union by the end of the war.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] However, while the design proved exceptionally well-suited for river combat, the low profile and heavy turret caused poor seaworthiness in rough waters.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Russia, fearing that the American Civil War would spill into Russian Alaska, launched ten sister ships, as soon as Ericsson's plans reached St.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] What followed has been described as *"Monitor mania"*.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The revolving turret later inspired similar designs for future warships, which eventually became the modern battleship.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The vulnerability of wooden hulls to armored ships was noted particularly in Britain and France, where the wisdom of the planned conversion of the battle fleet to armor was given a powerful demonstration.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Another feature that was emulated was not so successful.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Impressed by the ease with which *Virginia* had sunk *Cumberland*, naval architects began to incorporate rams into their hull designs.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The first purpose-built ram in the modern era was the French armored ram *Taureau*, whose guns were said to have "the sole function of preparing the way for the ram." The inclusion of rams in warship hull design persisted almost to the outbreak of World War I.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The name of the warship that served the Confederacy in the Battle of Hampton Roads has been a continuing source of confusion and some contention.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] She was originally a screw frigate in the United States Navy carrying the name USS *Merrimack*.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] All parties continued to use the name after her capture by secessionists while she was being rebuilt as an ironclad.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] When her conversion was almost complete, her name was officially changed to *Virginia*.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Despite the official name change, Union accounts persisted in calling *Merrimack* by her original name, while Confederate sources used either *Virginia* or *Merrimac(k)*.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The alliteration of *Monitor* and *Merrimack* has persuaded most popular accounts to adopt the familiar name, even when it is acknowledged to be technically incorrect.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] She was a paddle wheel steamer named for the victor (as most Southerners saw it) at Hampton Roads.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] She was used for running the blockade until she was captured and taken into Federal service, still named *Merrimac.* Her name was a spelling variant of the river, namesake of USS *Merrimack*.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Both spellings are still in use around the Hampton Roads area.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] A small community in Montgomery County, Virginia, near the location where the iron for the Confederate ironclad was forged is now known as Merrimac.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Some of the iron mined there and used in the plating on the Confederate ironclad is displayed at the Norfolk Naval Shipyard in Portsmouth.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The anchor of *Virginia* sits on the lawn in front of the American Civil War Museum in Richmond.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] After resting undetected on the ocean floor for 111 years, the wreck of *Monitor* was located by a team of scientists in 1973.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The remains of the ship were found upside down 16 mi (26 km) off Cape Hatteras, on a relatively flat, sandy bottom at a depth of about 240 ft (73 m).
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] In 1987, the site was declared a National Marine Sanctuary, the first shipwreck to receive this distinction.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Because of *Monitor*'s advanced state of deterioration, timely recovery of remaining significant artifacts and ship components became critical.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Numerous fragile artifacts, including the innovative turret and its two Dahlgren guns, an anchor, steam engine, and propeller, have been recovered.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] They were transported back to Hampton Roads to the Mariners' Museum in Newport News, Virginia, where they were treated in special tanks to stabilize the metal.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] It was reported that it would take about ten years for the metal to completely stabilize.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The new USS *Monitor* Center at the Mariners' Museum officially opened on March 9, 2007, and a full-scale copy of USS *Monitor*, the original recovered turret, and artifacts and related items are now on display.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The Battle of Hampton Roads was a significant event in both Naval and Civil War history that has been detailed in many books, televised Civil War documentaries, and in film, to include TNT's 1991 *Ironclads*.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] In New York City, where the designer of the Monitor, John Ericsson, died in March 1889, a statue was commissioned by the state to commemorate the battle between the Ironclads.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The statue features a stylized male nude allegorical figure on water between two iron cleats.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] In Virginia, the state dedicated the Monitor-Merrimack Overlook at Anderson Park on a jetty that overlooks the site of the battle.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The park contains several historical markers commemorating both ships.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Also, in 1992, Virginia dedicated the $400 million, 4.6-mile-long Monitor-Merrimac Memorial Bridge-Tunnel, which is located less than 1 mile from the site of the battle.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] The **Battle of Kinburn**, a combined land-naval engagement during the final stage of the Crimean War, took place on the tip of the Kinburn Peninsula (on the south shore of the Dnieper–Bug estuary in what is now Ukraine) on 17 October 1855.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] During the battle a combined fleet of vessels from the French Navy and the British Royal Navy bombarded Russian coastal fortifications after an Anglo-French ground force had besieged them.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] Three French ironclad batteries carried out the main attack, which saw the main Russian fortress destroyed in an action that lasted about three hours.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] The battle, although strategically insignificant with little effect on the outcome of the war, is notable for the first use of modern ironclad warships in action.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] Although frequently hit, the French ships destroyed the Russian forts within three hours, suffering minimal casualties in the process.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] This battle convinced contemporary navies to design and build new major warships with armour plating; this instigated a naval arms race between France and Britain lasting over a decade.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] In September 1854, the Anglo-French army that had been at Varna was ferried across the Black Sea and landed on the Crimean Peninsula.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] They then fought their way to the main Russian naval base on the peninsula, the city of Sevastopol, which they placed under siege.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] The Russian garrison eventually withdrew from the city in early September 1855, freeing the French and British fleets for other tasks.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] A discussion ensued over what target should be attacked next; the French and British high commands considered driving from the Crimea to Kherson and launching major campaigns in Bessarabia or the Caucasus.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] Instead, at the urging of French commanders, they settled on a smaller-scale operation to seize the Russian fort at Kinburn, which protected the mouth of the Dnieper.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] The British argued that to seize Kinburn without advancing to Nikolaev would only serve to warn the Russians of the threat to the port.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] Fox Maule-Ramsay, then the British Secretary of State for War, suggested that without a plan to exploit the capture of the fortress, the only purpose of the operation would be to give the fleets something to do.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] The fortress was located on the Kinburn Spit, at the extreme western end of the Kinburn Peninsula, and consisted of three separate fortifications.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] The primary fort, built of stone, square, and equipped with bastions, held 50 guns, some of which were mounted in protective casemates; the rest were in *en barbette* mountings, firing over the parapets.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] Two smaller fortresses were located further down the spit, mounting ten and eleven guns, respectively.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] The first was a small stone fort, while the second was a simple sand earthwork.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] The forts were armed only with medium and smaller calibre guns, the largest guns being 24-pounders.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] Major General Maxim Kokhanovitch commanded the garrison of 1,500 men, most of whom were stationed in the main fort.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] Across the estuary was Fort Nikolaev in the town of Ochakov with fifteen more guns, but these were too far away to play a role in the battle.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] To attack the forts, the British and French assembled a fleet centred on four French and six British ships of the line, led by British Rear Admiral Edmund Lyons and the French Vice Admiral Armand Joseph Bruat.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] The British contributed a further seventeen frigates and sloops, ten gunboats, and six bomb vessels, along with ten transport vessels.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] The French squadron included three corvettes, four avisos, twelve gunboats, and five bomb vessels.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] The transports carried a force of 8,000 men from French and British Army regiments that would be used to besiege the forts.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] In addition to the contingent of conventional sailing warships, the French squadron brought three experimental ironclad warships that had recently arrived from France.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] These, the first three ironclad batteries of the *Dévastation* class—*Lave*, *Dévastation*, and *Tonnante*—had been sent to the Black Sea in late July, but they arrived too late to take part in the siege of Sevastopol.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] These vessels, the first ironclad warships, carried eighteen 50-pounder guns and were protected with 4 inches (100 mm) of wrought iron armour.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] Observers speculated that these untested warships would be ineffective in combat, owing to their slow speed and poor handling.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] In an effort to confuse the Russians, the combined fleet made a feint westward toward Odessa on 8 October before turning east to Kinburn.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] The combined French and British fleet arrived off Kinburn on 14 October.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] That night, a force of nine gunboats escorted transports carrying 8,000 men, led by François Achille Bazaine, who were landed behind the forts, further up the peninsula.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] The gunboat force was commanded by Rear Admiral Houston Stewart, who ordered his crews to hold their fire in the darkness unless they were able to clearly see a Russian target.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] The Russians did not launch a counterattack on the landing, allowing the French and British soldiers to dig trench positions while the gunboats shelled the main fort, albeit ineffectively.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] By the morning of the 17th, the soldiers had completed significant entrenchments, with French troops facing the fortifications and British troops manning the outward defences against a possible Russian attempt to relieve the garrison.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] By this time, the French had begun building sapping trenches, which then came under fire from the Russian fortress.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] In the meantime, on the night of the 16th, a French vessel had taken depth soundings close to the main fort to determine how closely the ships could approach it.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] Throughout this time, heavy seas prevented the fleet from launching a sustained bombardment of the Russian positions.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] At around 9:00 on 17 October, the Anglo-French fleet moved into position to begin their bombardment.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] The ships of the line had a difficult time getting into effective positions owing to the shoals in the surrounding water, and so much of the work fell to smaller and shallower draught vessels, most prominently the three ironclad batteries.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] The floating batteries were anchored just 600 yards (550 m) from the Russian fortress, where they proved to be immune to Russian artillery fire, which either bounced off or exploded harmlessly on their wrought iron armour plating.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] The French and British ships of the line were anchored further out, at around 1,200 yards (1,100 m), while the bomb vessels were placed further still, at 2,800 yards (2,600 m).
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] While their guns battered at the fortifications, the ironclads each had a contingent of Royal Marines who inflicted significant casualties on the Russian gun crews.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] The only significant hit on the ironclad batteries was one shell that entered a gunport on *Dévastation*, which killed two men but otherwise caused no serious damage to the ship.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] The cannonade started fires in the main fortress and rapidly disabled Russian guns.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] Once Russian fire started to decrease, the gunboats moved into position behind the fortresses and began to bombard them as well.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] In the course of the morning, the three French vessels fired some 3,000 shells into the fort, and by 12:00, it had been neutralized by the combined firepower of the Anglo-French fleet.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] A single Russian hoisted a white flag above the fort to indicate their surrender, and Kokhanovitch walked out to speak with the French ground commander.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] According to historian James Grant, around 1,100 Russians of the 1,500-man garrison survived the battle and were allowed to leave without their weapons.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] Herbert Wilson puts the Russian casualties much lower, at 45 dead and 130 wounded.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] For the French and British, the only men killed were the two aboard *Dévastation*, with a further 25 wounded, all of whom were aboard the floating batteries.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] In the course of the battle, *Dévastation* was hit 75 times, while *Lave* received 66 hits and *Tonnante* was hit around the same number of times.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] None of the ships emerged from the battle with more than minor dents in their armour plate.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] On 20 October, Bazaine's infantry conducted reconnaissance toward Kherson and met no organized resistance before withdrawing.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] After they returned to Kinburn, the French and British commanders determined that the fort could be rebuilt and held through the upcoming winter.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] A force of 1,700 men was left behind to garrison the position, along with the three ironclad batteries.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] The rest of the force returned to the Crimea.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] Though the British had initially considered continuing up the Dnieper to capture Nikolaev, it became clear after the seizure of Kinburn that to do so would require much larger numbers of soldiers to clear the cliffs that dominated the river than had been originally estimated.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] The British planned to eventually launch an offensive to take Nikolaev in 1856, but the war ended before it could be begun.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] Since they lacked the forces to take Nikolaev in a single campaign, the seizure of Kinburn proved to have limited strategic effect.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] Nevertheless, the attack on Kinburn was significant in that it demonstrated that the French and British fleets had developed effective amphibious capabilities and had technological advantages that gave them a decisive edge over their Russian opponents.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] The destruction of Kinburn's coastal fortifications completed the Anglo-French naval campaign in the Black Sea; the Russians no longer had any meaningful forces left to oppose them at sea.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] The British and French navies planned to transfer forces to the Baltic Sea the following year to strengthen operations there.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] Diplomatic pressure from still-neutral Austria convinced Czar Alexander II of Russia to sue for peace, which was concluded the following February with the Treaty of Paris.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] Their success at Kinburn, coupled with the devastating effect new shell-firing guns had had on wooden warships at the Battle of Sinop earlier in the war led most French naval officers to support the new armoured vessels.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] Napoleon III's programme produced the first sea-going ironclad, *Gloire*, initiating a naval construction race between France and Britain that would last until the outbreak of the Franco-Prussian War in 1870.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] The British Royal Navy, which had five ironclad batteries under construction, laid down another four after the victory at Kinburn, and replied to *Gloire* with a pair of armoured frigates of their own, *Warrior* and *Black Prince*.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-kinburn-1855] France built a further eleven batteries built to three different designs, and the Russian Navy built fifteen armoured rafts for harbour defence.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] A **breechloader** is a firearm or artillery piece in which the user loads the ammunition from the breech (rear) end of the barrel.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The vast majority of modern firearms are breechloaders.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Before the mid-19th century, most guns were muzzleloaders, guns loaded from the muzzle (front) end of the barrel.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Only a few muzzle-loading weapons, such as mortars, rifle grenades, some rocket launchers, such as the Panzerfaust 3 and RPG-7, and the GP series grenade launchers, have remained in common usage in modern military conflicts.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] However, referring to a weapon explicitly as breech-loading is mostly limited to weapons in which the operator loads ammunition by hand (and not by operating a mechanism such as a bolt action), such as artillery pieces or break-action small arms.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Breech-loading designs provide several advantages, chief among which is reduced reload time.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Rather than having to push propellant and projectile through the whole length of the barrel and pack it down, they can be simply inserted into the chamber far quicker.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The reloading process itself is also streamlined, as the weapons do not need to be maneuvered around as much; for artillery, this also allows gun emplacements to be smaller and the crew to remain better protected.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Rifled or fouled barrels do not impede loading the breech.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Another advantage is that projectiles could be made to fit the bore tightly, increasing power, range and accuracy.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Unloading a breechloader is much easier as well, as the ammunition can be unloaded from the breech end, which can often be done by hand.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Unloading muzzleloaders requires drilling into the projectile to drag it out through the whole length of the barrel, and in some cases, the guns are simply fired to facilitate the unloading process.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The advent of breechloading gave a significant increase to effective firepower by its own right, and it also enabled further revolutions in firearm designs such as repeating and self-loading firearms.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Although breech-loading firearms were developed as far back as the early 14th century in Burgundy and various other parts of Europe, breech-loading became more successful with improvements in precision engineering and machining in the 19th century.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The main challenge for developers of breech-loading firearms was sealing the breech.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] That was eventually solved for smaller firearms by the development of the self-contained metallic cartridge in the mid-19th century.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] For firearms that are too large to use cartridges, the problem was solved by the development of the interrupted screw.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Breech-loading swivel guns were invented in the 14th century.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] They were a particular type of swivel gun, and consisted in a small breech-loading cannon equipped with a swivel for easy rotation, loaded by inserting a mug-shaped chamber already filled with powder and projectiles.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The breech-loading swivel gun had a high rate of fire, and was especially effective in anti-personnel roles.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Breech-loading firearms are known from the 16th century.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Henry VIII possessed one, which he apparently used as a hunting gun to shoot birds.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Meanwhile, in China, an early form of breech-loading musket, known as the Che Dian Chong, was known to have been created in the second half of the 16th century for the Ming dynasty's arsenals.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Like all early breech-loading fireams, gas leakage was a limitation and danger present in the weapon's mechanism.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] More breech-loading firearms were made in the early 18th century.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] One such gun known to have belonged to Philip V of Spain, and was manufactured circa 1715, probably in Madrid.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] It came with a ready-to load reusable cartridge.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Patrick Ferguson, a British Army officer, developed in 1772 the Ferguson rifle, a breech-loading flintlock firearm.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Roughly two hundred of the rifles were manufactured and used in the Battle of Brandywine, during the American Revolutionary War, but shortly after they were retired and replaced with the standard Brown Bess musket.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] From the late 18th century to early 19th century, and later on into the mid-19th century, there were attempts in Europe at an effective breech-loader.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] There were concentrated attempts at improved cartridges and methods of ignition.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The cartridge was loaded through the breech and fired with a needle.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The needle-activated central-fire breech-loading gun would become a major feature of firearms thereafter.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The corresponding firearm was also developed by Pauly.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Pauly made an improved version, which was protected by a patent on 29 September 1812.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The United States Army adopted the first standard breech-loading rifle, the Hall rifle of 1819, in large quantities.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The Pauly cartridge was further improved by the French gunsmith Casimir Lefaucheux in 1828, by adding a pinfire primer, but Lefaucheux did not register his patent until 1835: a pinfire cartridge containing powder in a cardboard shell.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] In 1842, the Norwegian Armed Forces adopted the breech-loading caplock, the Kammerlader, one of the first instances in which a modern army widely adopted a breech-loading rifle as its main infantry firearm.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] In 1845, another Frenchman Louis-Nicolas Flobert invented, for indoor shooting, the first rimfire metallic cartridge, constituted by a bullet fit in a percussion cap.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Usually derived in the 6 mm and 9 mm calibres, it is since then called the Flobert cartridge but it does not contain any powder; the only propellant substance contained in the cartridge is the percussion cap itself.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] In English-speaking countries the Flobert cartridge corresponds to the .22 BB and .22 CB ammunitions.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] In 1846, yet another Frenchman, Benjamin Houllier, patented the first fully metallic cartridge containing powder in a metallic shell.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Houllier commercialised his weapons in association with the gunsmiths Blanchard or Charles Robert.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] But the subsequent Houllier and Lefaucheux cartridges, even if they were the first full-metal shells, were still pinfire cartridges, like those used in the LeMat (1856) and Lefaucheux (1858) revolvers, although the LeMat also evolved in a revolver using rimfire cartridges.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The *Dreyse Zündnadelgewehr* (Dreyse needle gun) was a single-shot breech-loading rifle using a rotating bolt to seal the breech.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] It was so called because of its .5-inch needle-like firing pin, which passed through a paper cartridge case to impact a percussion cap at the bullet base.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] It began development in the 1830s under Johann Nicolaus von Dreyse and eventually an improved version of it was adopted by Prussia in the late 1840s.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The paper cartridge and the gun had numerous deficiencies; specifically, serious problems with gas leaking.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] However, the rifle was used to great success in the Prussian army in the Austro-Prussian War of 1866.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] This, and the Franco-Prussian War of 1870–71, eventually caused much interest in Europe for breech-loaders and the Prussian military system in general.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The first centrefire cartridge was introduced in 1855 by Pottet, with both Berdan and Boxer priming.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] In 1860, the New Zealand government petitioned the Colonial Office for more soldiers to defend Auckland.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The bid was unsuccessful and the government began instead making inquiries to Britain to obtain modern weapons.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] In 1861 they placed orders for the Calisher and Terry carbine, which used a breech-loading system using a bullet consisting of a standard Minié lead bullet in .54 calibre backed by a charge and tallowed wad, wrapped in nitrated paper to keep it waterproof.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The carbine had been issued in small numbers to English cavalry (Hussars) from 1857.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] About 3–4,000 carbines were brought into New Zealand a few years later.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The carbine was used extensively by the Forest Rangers, an irregular force led by Gustavus von Tempsky that specialized in bush warfare and reconnaissance.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Von Tempsky liked the short carbine, which could be loaded while lying down.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The waterproofed cartridge was easier to keep dry in the New Zealand bush.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Museums in New Zealand hold a small number of these carbines in good condition.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] During the American Civil War, at least nineteen types of breech-loaders were fielded.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The Sharps used a successful dropping block design.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The Greene used rotating bolt-action, and was fed from the breech.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The Spencer, which used lever-actuated bolt-action, was fed from a seven-round detachable tube magazine.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The Henry and Volcanic used rimfire metallic cartridges fed from a tube magazine under the barrel.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] These held a significant advantage over muzzle-loaders.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The improvements in breech-loaders had spelled the end of muzzle-loaders.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] To make use of the enormous number of war surplus muzzle-loaders, the Allin conversion Springfield was adopted in 1866.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] General Burnside invented a breech-loading rifle before the war, the Burnside carbine.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The French adopted the new Chassepot rifle in 1866, which was much improved over the Dreyse needle gun as it had dramatically fewer gas leaks due to its de Bange sealing system.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The British initially took the existing Enfield and fitted it with a Snider breech action (solid block, hinged parallel to the barrel) firing the Boxer cartridge.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Following a competitive examination of 104 guns in 1866, the British decided to adopt the Peabody-derived Martini-Henry with trap-door loading in 1871.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Single-shot breech-loaders would be used throughout the latter half of the 19th Century, but were slowly replaced by various designs for repeating rifles, first used in the American Civil War.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Manual breech-loaders gave way to manual magazine feed and then to self-loading rifles.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The first modern breech-loading rifled gun is a breech-loader invented by Martin von Wahrendorff with a cylindrical breech plug secured by a horizontal wedge in 1837.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] In the 1850s and 1860s, Joseph Whitworth and William Armstrong invented improved breech-loading artillery, the 12-pounder Whitworth rifle and the Armstrong gun.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The M1867 naval guns produced in Imperial Russia at the Obukhov State Plant used Krupp technology.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] A breech action is the loading sequence of a breech loading naval gun or small arm.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The earliest breech actions were either three-shot break-open actions or a barrel tip-down, remove the plug and reload actions.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The later breech-loaders included the Ferguson rifle, which used a screw-in/screw out action to reload, and the Hall rifle, which tipped up at 30 degrees for loading.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The better breech loaders, however, used percussion caps, including the Sharps rifle, using a falling block (or sliding block) action to reload.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] And then later on came the Dreyse needle gun that used a moving seal (bolt) to seal and expose the breech.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Later on, however, the Mauser M71/84 rifle used self-contained metallic cartridges and used a rotating bolt to open and close the breech.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] A **built-up gun** is artillery with a specially reinforced barrel.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] An inner tube of metal stretches within its elastic limit under the pressure of confined powder gases to transmit stress to outer cylinders that are under tension.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] Concentric metal cylinders or wire windings are assembled to minimize the weight required to resist the pressure of powder gases pushing a projectile out of the barrel.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] Built-up construction was the norm for guns mounted aboard 20th century dreadnoughts and contemporary railway guns, coastal artillery, and siege guns through World War II.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] The first built-up gun was designed by French artillery officer Alfred Thiéry in 1834 and tested not later than 1840.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] Also about 1840 another one was made by Daniel Treadwell, and yet another one was produced by Mersey Iron Works in Liverpool according to the John Ericsson's design.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] Sheffield architector John Frith received a patent on their manufacture in 1843.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] However, all these guns (whether made from cast iron, wrought iron or their combination) were not technologically practical before the 1850s.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] In the 1850s William Armstrong serially produced his rifled breechloaders with the same technology, and built-up, but very simple Parrott rifled muzzleloaders played a significant role in the US Civil War a decade later.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] Blakely rifles also participated in that war, but on another side.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] Starting from the 1860s, built-up Krupp guns became a commercial success in Continental Europe.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] Velocity and range of artillery vary directly with pressure of gunpowder or smokeless powder gases pushing the shell out of a gun barrel.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] A gun will deform (or explode) if chamber pressures strain the barrel beyond the elastic limit of the metal from which it is made.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] Thickness of homogeneous cast iron gun barrels reached a useful limit at approximately one-half caliber.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] Additional thickness provided little practical benefit, since higher pressures generated cracks from the bore before the outer portion of the cylinder could respond, and those cracks would extend outward during subsequent firings.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] By 1870s the technology was widely adopted.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] Claverino's 1876 treatise on the "Resistance of Hollow Cylinders" was published in *Giornale d'Artiglieria*.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] The concept was to give exterior portions of the gun initial tension, gradually decreasing toward the interior, while giving interior parts a normal state of compression by the outer cylinders and wire windings.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] Theoretical maximum performance would be achieved if the inner cylinder forming the rifled bore were compressed to its elastic limit by surrounding elements while at rest before firing, and expanded to its elastic limit by internal gas pressure during firing.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] The innermost cylinder forming the chamber and rifled bore is called a *tube* or, with certain construction techniques, a *liner*.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] A second layer cylinder called the *jacket* extends rearward past the chamber to house the breechblock.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] The jacket usually extends forward through the areas of highest pressure, through the recoil slide, and may extend all the way to the muzzle.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] The forward part of the barrel may be tapered toward the muzzle because less strength is required for reduced pressures as the projectile approaches it.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] This tapered portion of barrel is called the *chase*.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] Very large guns sometimes use shorter outer cylinders called *hoops* when manufacturing limitations make full length jackets impractical.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] Hoops forward of the slide are called *chase hoops*.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] The jacket or forward chase hoop may be flared outward in the form of a bell at the muzzle for extra strength to reduce splitting because the metal at that point is not supported on the forward end.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] As many as four or five layers, or hoop courses, of successively tensioned cylinders have been used.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] Layers are designated alphabetically as the "A" tube enclosed by the "B" jacket and chase hoops, enclosed by the "C" hoop course, enclosed by the "D" hoop course, etc.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] Individual hoops within a course are numbered from the breech forward as the B1 jacket, the B2 chase hoop, and then the C1 jacket hoop, the C2 hoop etc.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] Successive hoop course joints are typically staggered and individual hoop courses use lap joints in preference to butt joints to minimize the weakness of joint locations.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] Cylinder diameter may be varied by including machined *shoulders* to prevent forward longitudinal movement of an inner cylinder within an outer cylinder during firing.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] Shoulder locations are similarly staggered to minimize weakness.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] After the tube, jacket, and hoops have been machined to appropriate dimensions, the jacket is carefully heated to approximately 400 degrees Celsius (800 degrees Fahrenheit) in a vertical air furnace so thermal expansion allows the cool tube to be lowered into place.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] When the jacket is in position, it is cooled to form a tensioned shrink fit over the tube.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] Then the next hoop (either B2 or C1) is similarly heated so the assembled A tube and B1 jacket can be lowered into position for a successive shrink fit.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] The assembled unit may be machined prior to fitting a new hoop.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] The process continues as remaining tubes are heated sequentially and cooled onto the built-up unit until all elements have been assembled.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] When tensioned wire winding is used in place of a hoop course, the wire is typically covered by an outer tensioned cylinder also called a *jacket*.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] Burning powder gases melt part of the bore each time a gun is fired.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] This melted metal is oxidized or blown out of the muzzle until the barrel is eroded to the extent shell dispersion becomes unacceptable.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] After firing several hundred shells, a gun may be reconditioned by boring out the interior and inserting a new liner as the interior cylinder.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] Exterior cylinders are heated as a unit to approximately 200 degrees Celsius (400 degrees Fahrenheit) to allow insertion of a new liner and the liner is bored and rifled after installation.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] A new liner may be bored for a different projectile diameter than used in the original gun.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] Liners may be either cylindrical or conical.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] Conical liners are tapered toward the muzzle for ease of removal from the breech end while limiting forward creep during firing.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] Conical liners may be removed by water cooling the liner after re-heating the barrel, but cylindrical liners must be bored out.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] With the obsolescence of very large guns following World War II, metallurgical advances encouraged use of monoblock (one-piece) construction for postwar guns of medium caliber.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] In a procedure called autofrettage, a bored monoblock tube is filled with hydraulic fluid at pressures higher than the finished gun will experience during firing.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] Upon release of hydraulic pressure, the internal diameter of the monoblock tube will have been increased by approximately 6%.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/built-up-gun] The outer portion of the finished monoblock rebounds to approximately its original diameter and exerts compressive forces on the inner portion similar to the separate cylinders of a built-up gun.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] It is measured in inches or in millimeters.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] Since metric and US customary units do not convert evenly at this scale, metric conversions of caliber measured in decimal inches are typically approximations of the precise specifications in non-metric units, and vice versa.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] In a rifled barrel, the distance is measured between opposing lands (minor diameter) or between opposing grooves (major diameter); groove measurements are common in cartridge designations originating in the United States, while land measurements are more common elsewhere in the world.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] Measurements "across the grooves" are used for maximum precision because rifling and the specific caliber so measured is the result of final machining process which cuts grooves into the rough bore, leaving the "lands" behind.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] Good performance requires a concentric, straight bore that accurately centers the projectile within the barrel, in preference to a "tight" fit which can be achieved even with off-center, crooked bores that cause excessive friction, fouling and an out-of-balance, wobbling projectile in flight.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] There is much variance in the use of the term "small-bore", which over the years has changed considerably, with anything under 0.577 inches (14.7 mm) considered "small-bore" prior to the mid-19th century.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] While modern firearms are generally referred to by the name of the cartridge the gun is chambered for, they are still categorized together based on bore diameter.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] For example, a firearm might be described as a "30 caliber rifle", which could accommodate any of a wide range of cartridges using a roughly 0.30 inches (7.6 mm) projectile; or as a "22 rimfire", referring to any rimfire firearms firing cartridges with a 22 caliber projectile.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] However, there can be significant differences in nominal bullet and bore dimensions, and all cartridges so "categorized" are not automatically identical in actual caliber.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] For example, 303 British firearms and projectiles are often "categorized" as ".30-caliber" alongside several dozen U.S.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] "30-caliber" cartridges despite using bullets of .310–.312-inch (7.87–7.92 mm) diameter while all U.S.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] "30-caliber" centerfire rifle cartridges use a common, standard .308-inch (7.82 mm) bullet outside diameter.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] Using bullets larger than design specifications causes excessive pressures, while undersize bullets cause low pressures, insufficient muzzle velocities and fouling that will eventually lead to excessive pressures.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] Makers of early cartridge arms had to invent methods of naming cartridges since no established convention existed then.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] One of the early established cartridge arms was the Spencer repeating rifle, which Union forces used in the American Civil War.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] It was named based on the chamber dimensions, rather than the bore diameter, with the earliest cartridge called the "No.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] 56 cartridge", indicating a chamber diameter of .56 in; the bore diameter varied considerably, from .52 to .54 in.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] Later various derivatives were created using the same basic cartridge, but with smaller-diameter bullets; these were named by the cartridge diameter at the base and mouth.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] The 56–52, the most common of the new calibers, used a 50-cal bullet.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] Other black powder-era cartridges used naming schemes that appeared similar, but measured entirely different characteristics; 45-70, 44-40, and 32-20 were designated by bullet diameter to hundredths of an inch and standard black powder charge in grains.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] Optionally, the bullet weight in grains was designated, such as 45-70-405.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] This scheme was far more popular and was carried over after the advent of early smokeless powder cartridges such as the 30-30 Winchester and 22 Long.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] Later developments used terms to indicate relative power, such as .44 Special and .44 Magnum.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] Variations on these methods persist today, with new cartridges such as the 204 Ruger and 17 HMR (Hornady Magnum Rimfire).
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] Metric diameters for small arms refer to cartridge dimensions and are expressed with an "×" between the bore diameter and the length of the cartridge case; for example, the 6.5×55mm Swedish cartridge has a bore diameter of 6.5 mm and a case length of 55 mm.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] The means of measuring a rifled bore varies, and may refer to the diameter of the lands or the grooves of the rifling.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] For example, the 257 Roberts and 250 Savage both use a .257 inch projectile; both 250 Savage and 257 Roberts rifle bores have a .250 inch land diameter and .257 inch groove diameter.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] The .308 Winchester is measured across the grooves and uses a .308-in diameter (7.82-mm) bullet; the military-specification version is known as 7.62 × 51 mm NATO, so called because the bore diameter measured between the lands is 7.62 mm, and the cartridge has a case 51 mm long.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] Converting a rifle to fire a different cartridge in the same bore diameter, often involves merely re-chambering the barrel to the new cartridge dimensions, if the rim diameter of the new cartridge matches that of the old cartridge.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] Converting a rifle to fire a different cartridge in a different caliber and bore as what it initially was, means that the barrel of the rifle will also need to be changed.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] There are a few important factors to consider when converting a rifle to a different caliber or cartridge.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] The action of the rifle should be long enough to contain the new cartridge, the magazine should also be able to hold the new cartridge, the bolt face should be the correct diameter and the extractor the correct size to hold the head of the new cartridge.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] The most common of these caliber conversions on rifles, are usually done to change from a parent cartridge to a new cartridge based on it, like when converting a rifle to a 6.5 mm Creedmoor from a 308 Winchester on which it is based.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] The following table lists some of the commonly used calibers where both metric and US customary units are used as equivalents.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] Due to variations in naming conventions, and the whims of the cartridge manufacturers, bullet diameters can vary widely from the diameter implied by the name.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] For example, a difference of 0.045 in (1.15 mm) occurs between the smallest and largest of the several cartridges designated as ".38 caliber".
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] Shotguns are classed according to gauge, a related expression.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] The gauge of a shotgun refers to how many lead spheres, each with a diameter equal to that of the bore, that amounts to one pound (454 g (1.0 lb)) in weight.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] In the case of a 12-gauge (18.5 mm) shotgun, it would take 12 spheres the size of the shotgun's bore to equal a pound.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] A numerically larger gauge indicates a smaller barrel: a 20-gauge (15.6 mm) shotgun requires more spheres to equal a pound; therefore, its barrel is smaller than the 12-gauge.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] This metric is used in Russia as "caliber number": e.g., "shotgun of the 12 caliber." The 16th caliber is known as "lordly" (Russian: барский).
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] While shotgun bores can be expressed in calibers (the .410 bore shotgun is measured as .410 in (10.4 mm) in diameter, unlike with rifles the actual bore diameter of a smoothbore shotgun varies significantly down the length of the barrel, with the use of chokes and back-boring.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] In the United Kingdom, "gauge" is referred to as "bore" and in the United States "bore" is referred to as "gauge", e.g. a "12-bore shotgun or 12-gauge shotgun" has a bore or gauge that can accommodate a lead sphere weighing 1/12th of a pound.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] The term caliber is used as a measure of length of artillery barrels from muzzle to breech, expressed as a multiple of the bore diameter.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] For example, a 4-inch gun of 50 calibers would have a barrel 4 in × 50 = 200 in long (written as 4" L/50 or 4"/50).
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] Both 14-in and 16-in navy guns were common in World War II.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] The British Royal Navy insisted on 50-cal guns on ships as it would allow 1,900 to 2,700 lb (860 to 1,220 kg) shells to travel at an initial velocity of up to 1,800 mph (2,897 km/h) to a distance of 26 mi (42 km).
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] Smoothbore cannon and carronade bores are designated by the weight in imperial pounds of spherical solid iron shot of diameter to fit the bore.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] Standard sizes are 6, 12, 18, 24, 32, and 42 pounds, with some non-standard weights using the same scheme.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] From about the mid-17th until the mid-19th century, the measurement of the bore of large gunpowder weapons was usually expressed as the weight of its iron shot in pounds.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] Iron shot was used as the standard reference because iron was the most common material used for artillery ammunition during that period, and solid spherical shot the most common form encountered.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] Artillery was classified thereby into standard categories, with the 3-pounder, 4-pounder, 6-pounder, 8-pounder, 9-pounder, 12-pounder, 18-pounder, 24-pounder, and 32-pounder being the most common sizes encountered, although larger, smaller and intermediate sizes existed.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] In practice, though, significant variation occurred in the actual mass of the projectile for a given nominal shot weight.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] The country of manufacture is a significant consideration when determining bore diameters.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] For example, the French livre, until 1812, had a mass of 489.5 g (1.079 lb), whilst the contemporary English (avoirdupois) pound massed of approximately 454 g (1.001 lb).
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] Thus, a French 32-pounder at the Battle of Trafalgar threw a shot with 1.138 kg (2.51 lb) more mass than an English 32-pounder.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] Complicating matters further, muzzle-loaded weapons require a significant gap between the sides of the tube bore and the surface of the shot.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] This is necessary so the projectile may be inserted from the mouth to the base of the tube and seated securely adjacent the propellant charge with relative ease.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] The gap, called windage, increases the size of the bore with respect to the diameter of the shot somewhere between 10% and 20% depending upon the year the tube was cast and the foundry responsible.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] The relationship between bore diameter and projectile weight was severed following the widespread adoption of rifled weapons during the latter part of the 19th century.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] Guns continued to be classed by projectile weight into the mid-20th century, particularly in British service with guns, such as the 2-pounder, 6-pounder, and 17-pounder anti-tank weapons.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/caliber] However, this value no longer definitively related to bore diameter, since projectiles were no longer simple spheres—and in any case were more often hollow shells filled with explosives rather than solid iron shot.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] Canister shot consists of a closed metal cylinder typically loosely filled with round lead or iron balls packed with sawdust to add more solidity and cohesion to the mass and to prevent the balls from crowding each other when the round was fired.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] The canister itself was usually made of tin, often dipped in a lacquer of beeswax diluted with turpentine to prevent corrosion of the metal.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] Iron was substituted for tin for larger-caliber guns.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] The ends of the canister were closed with wooden or metal disks.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] A cloth cartridge bag containing the round's gunpowder used to fire the canister from the gun barrel could be attached to the back of the metal canister for smaller caliber cannon.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] A sabot of wood, metal, or similar material was sometimes used to help the round during firing from the cannon.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] Various types of canister were devised for specific models of artillery field pieces.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] In 1753, the "secret howitzer", a special gun with an oval bore—intended to spread shot even wider—was briefly introduced into Russian service, but ultimately proved unsuccessful.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] The Royal Artillery Museum at Woolwich, London, holds examples of two early 18th century experimental French wide bore cannon—flattened tubes intended to scatter canister wide but in one horizontal plane.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] The United States Army developed a canister round, the M1028, for the M1 Abrams' 120 mm smoothbore gun in time for the 2003 invasion of Iraq.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] The effect is to turn a large-caliber gun on an armored fighting vehicle into a giant shotgun.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] This can be used against enemy infantry even when in proximity to friendly armoured vehicles, as the projectiles do not penetrate armour.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] In addition it can be used to create entry points to buildings, reduce wire obstacles and clear heavy vegetation, as well as strike low flying aircraft and helicopters.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] At times when the supply of balls were limited, nails, scrap iron or lead, wire, and other similar metal objects were included.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] The projectile had been known since at least the 16th century and was known by various nicknames in the 17th century such as hailshot or partridge shot.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] Rounds recovered from Henry VIII's warship *Mary Rose* (sunk 1545) were wooden cylinders filled with broken flint flakes.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] When filled with rubbish or scrap (rather than round bullets) the round could be known as scrapshot or langrage.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] In 1718, Blackbeard armed his guns with a range of makeshift weaponry including langrage.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] Several of his cannons, still loaded with spikes and shot, have been recovered from the wreck site of his flagship, the *Queen Anne's Revenge*.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] Archaeologists have also retrieved conglomerations of lead shot, nails, spikes and glass from the site.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] Langrage was also found among the artifact assemblage of the *Mardi Gras* shipwreck, 4,000 ft (1219 m) deep in the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] When fired, the canister disintegrates and its shards and projectiles spread out in a conical formation, causing a wide swath of destruction.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] It was particularly effective during the Napoleonic Wars and the American Civil War, where massed troops at close range (usually less than 400 yards) could be broken up by artillery batteries firing canister.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] At times, particularly at very close range, artillery crews would fire extremely lethal "double canister," where two rounds were loaded into the gun tube and fired simultaneously using a single charge.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] At the Battle of Waterloo, in 1815, Mercer's Troop, Royal Horse Artillery, fired a roundshot and a canister from each gun as a double-shot.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] The roundshot was loaded first with the canister on top.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] Canister played a key role for Union forces during their defeat of Confederate troops in Pickett's Charge during the Battle of Gettysburg in July 1863.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] In 1864 at the Battle of Brice's Cross Roads the Confederates used this method.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] At times, trained artillerists would fire the canister shot towards the ground in front of advancing enemy troops, causing the conical pattern to flatten out as the balls ricocheted and skipped off the terrain.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] This in effect widened the killing zone.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] An example of this tactic was on the first day of Gettysburg, where Lt.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] Artillery on Seminary Ridge skipped canister shot at Alfred M.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] Scales's approaching Confederate infantry, breaking up their attack and forcing them to take cover in a depression.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] Canister shot was also used to good effect by U.S.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] Marine 37 mm anti-tank guns in World War II to break up Japanese banzai charges.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] During the Korean War United Nations tanks experienced close-range massed infantry attacks from Communist forces.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] As a consequence a canister-type tank round was introduced to "sweep" enemy infantry off friendly tanks without harming friendly tank crews, who were behind canister-proof armor.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] UK weapons known to have fielded a canister round are the 76 mm and 105 mm tank guns and the 120 mm MOBAT and WOMBAT recoilless anti-tank guns.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] Shrapnel shells—named for the inventor, British artillery officer Henry Shrapnel—were developed from canister during the Napoleonic Wars and were intended to deliver the same canister effect, but at much longer ranges.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] As a result, its early designation was "spherical case shot".
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] Instead of a tin can filled with metal balls, the shrapnel shells carry a small powder charge to break open the case and disperse the shrapnel.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] Grapeshot was a geometric arrangement of round shot packed tightly into a canvas bag and separated from the gunpowder charge by a metal disk of full bore diameter.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] Grapeshot used fewer but larger projectiles than were contained within canister or shrapnel shells.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] Case shot broadly describes any multi-projectile artillery ammunition.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] The canister round is known as a case, so canister was sometimes called case shot and the term has confusingly become generic for grapeshot and shrapnel shells.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] However, the term case shot is also used to describe a hollow ball containing a powder charge and bullets.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canister-shot] After firing the iron ball the powder would explode, scattering the bullets.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The **Canon de 19 C modèle 1864** was a 194 mm cast iron rifled breech loader built-up gun used by the French Navy, as coastal artillery, and also in land warfare.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The first series of rifled guns made for the French Navy was known as 'Modèle 1858-60'.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] It came shortly after the 1855 Battle of Kinburn and consisted of seven hooped / ringed guns in the calibers 14, 16, and 22 cm.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] All but one of these were rifled muzzle loaders.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The 14 cm pieces were basically changed 18-pounders.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The 16 cm guns were transformed 30-pounders, except for the breech-loading one.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The 22 cm gun was a transformed shell gun.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The 22 cm shell gun weighed only about the same as the heavy 36-pounder (174.8 mm) guns.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] It therefore did not show the same relation between smoothbore and rifled calibers.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] A new series of rifled guns called 'modèle 1864', later 'modèle 1864-1866' was designed after the 1862 Battle of Hampton Roads.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] This battle made it clear that the existing 14 and 16 cm guns were not strong enough to effectively penetrate armored ships.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] Compared to the previous series, the modèle 1864 system raised the weight of the projectiles from about twice to about thrice the weight of the solid round bullet.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The charge was increased to about one-sixth of the weight of the projectile.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The modèle 1864 system also introduced three new calibers: our 'Canon de 19 C modèle 1864', the Canon de 24 C modèle 1864 and the Canon de 27 C modèle 1864.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The caliber of 194 mm for our 19 cm gun seems strange.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] However, in 1849 a smoothbore 50-pounder muzzleloading gun had been introduced in the French Navy.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] This 50-pounder gun had a caliber of 194 mm, but with a length of bore of 3,094 mm and a weight of 4,710 kg, it was much smaller.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The 50-pounder gun might explain the 194 mm caliber of the Canon de 19 C modèle 1864.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] When the model 1864 guns were introduced, the 19 cm gun was said to also be able to fire a round bullet of 25 kg.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] This would be practical if it was the same bullet that the 50-pounder fired.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The first designs of the Canon de 19 C modèle 1864 date from October and December 1864.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] There were e.g. guns with a single and (multiple arrangements of) double layers of rings.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] Other changes were internal, e.g. to the breech, the obturator(s) and the grooving.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The Canon de 19 C modèle 1864 T 1870 was a 19 cm model 1864 gun changed to be like the Canon de 19 C modèle 1870.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The primary reason for this change was the invention of slower burning gunpowders.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] These made it possible to use a higher charge without increasing the peak pressure, but while still yielding a useful high pressure over a longer period of time.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The changes consisted of inserting a steel inner tube into the gun and increasing the size of the powder chamber.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The new inner tube got the same rifling as the model 1870 gun.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The total length of the barrel was 3,800 mm or L/19.6.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The core of the cast iron barrel was reinforced by shrinking on hoops or rings, which pressed the cast iron closer together, making it more resistant to shock.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] Multiple systems of ringing the gun were tried out.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The first system consisted of a single layer of rings.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] Later on three different systems with a double layer of rings were introduced and put into service.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The final model had seven rings in the first layer and four in the second layer.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The length of bore of the barrel was 3,506 mm.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The main part of the barrel was 2,980 mm long and had a diameter of 194 mm.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] Behind the main barrel, there was a transitional cone that led to the powder chamber.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The powder chamber had a diameter of 205 mm.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] According to its final design, it was 506.5 mm long.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The obturator came right behind the powder chamber.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] It served to prevent the escape of gasses to the rear.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] It was a ring placed in a tronconic area that ranged from 214 to 216 mm diameter.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] Later on a second area was made that could be used in case the first became unserviceable.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] This second area had a diameter ranging from 225 to 228 mm.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] It was inserted into an area that was 219.5 mm long and had a diameter of 252 mm.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] At the muzzle these were 41.5 mm wide and had a maximum depth of 4 mm.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] Groove number 1 differed from the others, because it also served to guide the projectile to its proper position, the studs being in the grooves before firing the gun.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] For this purpose it was connected to a channel (*rigole*) that started outside the chamber.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The regular grenade of the 19 cm gun was an ogive cast iron grenade called *obus oblong*.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] At its head, a percussion fuze was mounted before firing.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The front studs (these went into the grooves) were made from zinc.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The studs at the rear were made of monetary bronze.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] This projectile weighed 52.25 kg and held 2.2 kg of explosives.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The obus oblong of chilled cast iron was also a grenade.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] It weighed 75 kg and had an internal explosive charge of 1 kg.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] It did not have a fuze, but relied on the heat of the impact to ignite the charge.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] See the image to the right, showing the internal lines of these grenades.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The first steel shot was called 'Boulet ogival de 19 cent. en acier'.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] It was a good option for penetrating armor and weighed 75 kg.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The 'Boulet ogival de 19 c/m en fonte dure' was the chilled cast iron equivalent of the same weight.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] It was slightly longer than the steel shot to get to the same weight.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The 'Boulet ogival de 19 c/m en fonte ordinaire' was a cast iron shot for exercises.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] It was like the steel and chilled cast iron shot, but still longer, to get the same weight.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] All these shot did not have an internal charge.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] For use on the shortest distances, there was less pointy cylindrical shot.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] There was a steel cylindrical projectiles for the most dire circumstances.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] To exercise with them, there was a cast iron cylindrical shot of the same weight, but again a bit longer to compensate for the density of iron instead of steel.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The set of projectiles was completed by three different kinds of canister shot.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The longest projectiles were 380 mm long.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The Canon de 19 C modèle 1864 T 1870 used the same projectiles as the model 1870 gun.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] With a charge of 8 kg, the regular grenade of 52.5 kg attained a velocity of 356 m/s.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] As the regular grenade relied on its explosion to cause damage, its range and accuracy were most important.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] On e.g. the battery carriage M 1867, it could be elevated to 12° and attain a range of about 3,900 m.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] Mounted on an upper deck carriage, it could attain a range of 7,000 m if it could be elevated to 35°.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] With a charge of 12.5 kg, the ogive massive armor-piercing shot of 75 kg attained a velocity of 344 m/s.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The ballistic table for this projectile went up to 800 m, which can be taken as the maximum effective range of the A-P shot.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The Canon de 19 C modèle 1864 T 1870 used the model 1870 projectiles and higher charges.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] For the regular grenade, this was 20 kg, for the ogive A-P projectile it was 21 kg, and for the exercise grenade it was 12 kg.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] For use on the upper deck, there were three models of a directing bar carriage (affût à flèche directrice).
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] These were named for a bar (*flèche*) that traversed on a pivot near the hull in front of the gun.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] In firing position, this lifted the upper carriage off the deck, making it easier to aim the gun horizontally.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The first carriage was made of wood, later ones of iron.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] However, this type of carriage soon proved inconvenient for guns that were as heavy as the 19 cm M 1864 and 1870, and so these carriages were abandoned.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The last model of these carriages could elevate the gun to 20°, decline it to 5° and weighed 2,835 kg.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The second type of carriage were the affûts de batterie à châssis.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] As the name implies, these were meant to be used on the covered gun deck of ironclads.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] These carriages consisted of an upper carriage (very much like a traditional naval carriage) that recoiled back over a frame called slide.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] Carriage and slide were built to create a lot of friction.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] A compressor brake connected to both would catch the rest of the movement.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The battery carriage M 1864 had a wooden upper carriage and a wooden slide.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] All M1864s were later changed to an use an iron slide, together with other modifications for using the carriages on floating batteries.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] Some of the M 1864s escaped these changes and were instead changed to be used on a turntable for small vessels.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The battery carriage M 1866 carriage had a cast iron slide from the start, but retained the wooden upper carriage.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] In 1868 all of these, like the M 1864 carriages would be changed to be used on floating batteries.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] After these changes, it could elevate the gun to 19° (16° for the M 1864).
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The battery carriage M 1867 was the third model for use on the battery deck.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] It could elevate the gun to 12° and incline it to 9.3° and weighed 3,760 kg.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] A fifth carriage was named 'système Dard' and was especially built for floating batteries.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The central pivot carriages (affût à châssis tournant) were meant for fast corvettes which were armed with three 19 cm M 1864 or M 1870 guns or for avisos, in which case the carriage was also called as such.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] Some of these carriages were changed for use on the Crocodile gunboats.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The carriages weighed about 7,358 kg including the rails.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] They could elevate the gun from -6° to +25°.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The turntable carriages (affûts à plate-forme tournante) were designed for the Alma-class armored corvettes.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] They had a sheet iron platform that turned on 12 rollers.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] Upon this platform the slide of the gun was fixed.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] This carriage weighed 13,623 kg including the platform and the rails.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] It could elevate the gun from -6° to +30°.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] A coastal carriage that turned on a front pivot was the affût de côte à pivot à l'avant pour canons rayés de 19 centimètres.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] Like the on board carriages, this had an upper carriage, a slide, a pivot, and an inverted semi-circular rails on the ground into which the rollers fit.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] Below the gun, there was generally a concrete slab of about 50 cm thickness.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The M 1869 used a compressor brake, while models M 1880, and M 1869M and M 1880M had a hydraulic brake.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] There was also a carriage on a central pivot, the M 1878.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] Opting for a front or a central pivot generally depended on whether the arc of fire required of the gun justified the costlier central pivot carriage.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The Canon de 19 C modèle 1864 was used extensively in coastal batteries.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The gun was also used during the Siege of Paris (1870–1871).
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] Two pieces were in battery at the fortress of Fort Mont-Valérien.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] Another piece was the gun called 'La Joséphine', but this was not used during the siege.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] It was used during the fighting of the Paris Commune.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] A handful of other pieces was used during the siege.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] In 1869 the ironclad the French ironclad Gloire got two Canon de 19 C modèle 1864 as chase guns on the upper deck.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] In 1876 Couronne got four 19 cm M 1864 guns on affûts à châssis on the upper deck.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] In 1866 *Solférino* (and probably *Magenta*) got 12 19 C modèle 1864 guns on its higher gun deck.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] These were later removed, but by December 1868 she was to get four 19 C modèle 1864 guns on the upper deck.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The Provence-class ironclads would also get four 19 C modèle 1864 guns on the upper deck after re-armament.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The smaller Belliqueuse initially had four 19 C modèle 1864 on affûts de batterie à châssis, but these were later replaced by M 1870 guns.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The floating battery *Opiniâtre* had four 19 C modèle 1864 guns on carriages with wooden frames.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The floating battery Implacable initially had the same armament and retained two 19 C modèle 1864 guns when she became a schooling vessel.
[src:canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-19-c-modèle-1864] The floating batteries *Embuscade*, *Protectrice*, *Refuge*, and *Imprenable* also got four 19 C modèle 1864 guns.
